Standard Variables
******************

The use of variables fo tools generating reports belongs to the
following topics:


 @{" Naming Scheme " Link "Naming Scheme"}                Variable names follow this scheme
 @{" Tool Specific Names " Link "Tool Specific Names"}          ... for differencing
 @{" Search Order " Link "Search Order"}                 How to search variables in @{b}ums.config@{ub}


@EndNode

@Node "Naming Scheme" "reportguide.guide/Naming Scheme"
@Next "Tool Specific Names"
@Prev "Variables"
@Toc "Variables"

Naming Scheme For Variables
===========================

The names of the variables used by tools generating reports are built
according to the scheme "Report.<o>", where "<o>" is a name of an
option. The variables can exist global but also local for the user using
the tool. Local variables have higher priority. See @{"Search Order" Link "Search Order"}, for
details.

   The standard names (and settings(1)) for <o> are:

User
     If set, all reports will be sent to this user.  Template:
     Name/A,Address

Folder
     If set, mails go into the folder <Report.Folder> of the user
     <Report.User>.

Group
     If set, a message will generated in group <Report.Group>. The UMS
     field @{b}ToName@{ub} is set to the contents of <Report.User>.

ReplyTo
     If set, the mail or public message gets the @{b}ReplyTo@{ub} address
     <Report.ReplyTo>. This should be an address of a real person, who
     can handle complains and something like that: postmaster@...
     Template: Name/A,Address

     This variable defaults to "Sysop".

<ToolName>
     If the contents of this variable starts with "N" or "n", the tool
     <ToolName> does not generate a report.

If the report shall be sent by mail, "Report.User" must be set; optional
"Report.Folder", too. If the reports shall go into a group,
"Report.Group" must be set.

   If "Report.User" and "Report.Group" are set, a mail @{i}and@{ui} a public
message has to be generated.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  All settings can be written in UMS-common multiple line
entries. So, for example, a report message can have more than one
recipient. If programmers have difficulties to read out a multi-line
variable, they can ask Hartmut Goebel <hartmut@oberon.sub.org> for a
suitable procedure.


@EndNode

@Node "Tool Specific Names" "reportguide.guide/Tool Specific Names"
@Next "Search Order"
@Prev "Naming Scheme"
@Toc "Variables"

Tool Specific Variable Names
============================

Sometimes it is not desirable that one user gets the reports of all
tools. For example, SetExpire shall send reports to postmaster and
FakeTool shall send reports to fakeuser. So variable names are possible,
which have the scheme "Report.<tool>.<o>". E.g. the @{b}ums.config@{ub} entry
@{b}(Report.faketool.ReplyTo "Joe Fake, fakeuser@host")@{ub} means that all
replies to FakeTool's reports shall be sent to Joe Fake.


@EndNode

@Node "Search Order" "reportguide.guide/Search Order"
@Prev "Tool Specific Names"
@Toc "Variables"

Search Order For Variables
==========================

The following search order has to be used with neither @{i}Global_Only@{ui} nor
@{i}Local_Only@{ui} set.

     Report.<tool>.<o>
     Report.<o>

This will lead to the following search order to be applied by UMS:

     Report.<tool>.<o>  (local)
     Report.<tool>.<o>  (global)
     Report.<o>         (local)
     Report.<o>         (global)


@EndNode

@Node "Header" "reportguide.guide/Header"
@Next "Contents"
@Prev "Variables"
@Toc "Main"

Contents Of The Message Header
******************************

The header of the public message or mail (private message) shall have
the following form:

     FromName:  <login user name(1) of tool>
     ReplyTo:   <value of "Report.Reply", default: "Sysop">
     Subject:   <tool's name>: <eventually some text> Report
     Attributs: RECEIPT
     Comments:  <tool's version string>

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1)  Whenever an UMS tool is called up to run it needs a name and a
password to log into the message base (see @{"UMS Login Guide" Link "loginguide.guide/General"}). This name
normally specifies the name of the user who is using the tool.


@EndNode

@Node "Contents" "reportguide.guide/Contents"
@Next "Status"
@Prev "Header"
@Toc "Main"

Contents Of A Report Message
****************************

The contents of a report has no fixed form. It does not have to be like
the output to StdOut. But it shall present the executed actions in a
suitable form and also contain error messages in case of need.


 @{" Error Messages " Link "Error Messages"}               Where to output error messages


@EndNode

@Node "Error Messages" "reportguide.guide/Error Messages"
@Prev "Contents"
@Toc "Contents"

Where To Output Error Messages
==============================

Here some guidelines to output error messages:

Fatal errors
     are written into the UMS logfile, to StdOut and in the report.

User errors
     go into the report and to StdOut.

System messages
     are sent as report only to the user specified by the report
     variables (see @{"Naming Scheme" Link "Naming Scheme"}).

Progress indicator(s)
     of a tool are only displayed on StdOut.


@EndNode

@Node "Status" "reportguide.guide/Status"
@Next "Author"
@Prev "Contents"
@Toc "Main"

Status Of A Report Message
**************************

All created report messages shall be set to "new" for all users (even
for the loginuser), i.e. by using the UMS tag @{b}NoUpdate = FALSE@{ub}.
Exporter are excepted from this rule: They have to set own report
messages for themselves to "old" to prevent errors (i.e. write the
report using the UMS tag @{b}NoUpdate = TRUE@{ub} oder leave the tag
unspecified).


@EndNode

